Introduction

This project was executed by the User Research Team in collaboration with Vincent Schalk and Tom Müller from the Sales Department. For one of our major clients Betway we ran an exclusive user survey in 3 markets between January and March 2020. The survey is part of a contractual agreement between both parties. This document contains a summary of the execution and the respective data analysis.

Participant Demographics

This survey was conducted in Germany, the UK and Spain, upon Betway’s request. No further selection has been made before sending out the survey. We targeted people in the given markets who speak the country’s native language (German in Germany, etc.).

Age distribution

Due to the betting topic in which these surveys act, we agreed to focus on all Onefootball users older than 18 years old.1 Learning: The largest group of participants is the “18-24” age group. UK is the youngest market of the three. A quarter of participants in Germany qualify as 55 years or older.

market 18-24 25-29 30-34 35-39 40-44 45-49 50-54 55+
Germany 32.64% 8.03% 6.16% 6.2% 6.21% 6.69% 9.78% 24.3%
Spain 55.36% 6.33% 4.59% 4.26% 5.23% 5.65% 5.29% 13.29%
UK 57.12% 8.14% 4.86% 4.36% 4.22% 4.2% 4.05% 13.06%

In the next question, Betway was interested in asking our users Who bets online at least once per month? The following table shows the frequency of betting, split by market.2 Learning: While observing that the majority of participants has never placed a bet before, Germany (20%), Spain (20%) and the UK (25%) have a significant share of active betters. Comparing this to the Onefootball user survey from December 2018, the number of people in Germany who never placed a bet has decreased from 73% to 58%.

Resons for not betting

Those who said they never bet, we asked what is the main reason. For all three markets, there is three main reasons for not betting: Risk aversion (scared of developing an addiction, and risk of losing money), but interestingly, especially in Germany, betting is also not perceived as an entertaining activity.

Reduction of sample

For the core part of the survey, we only include those users, who said to bet at least once per month. These participants will remain for further analysis. Due to the applied logics and length of the survey, we observed a continuous decrease in sample size, meaning later questions were answered by fewer people than earlier questions.

market Sample Size
Germany 1937
Spain 884
UK 1935

We can observe that the majority of participants spend 50 or less per month on sports betting.

Brand recognition

Open recognition

The participants were asked What are the three online sports betting brands that come to your mind first? straight from their head. Since the question does not indicate preference order, all answers from the three text fields were thrown into one pool. For each market, the following table is sorted by most named. We added different spelling variations that we found together.

Market First Second Third
Germany Tipico (798x) Bwin (423x) Betway (111x)
Spain Bet365 (193x) Sportium (112x) Codere (99x)
UK Bet365 (576x) Skybet (402x) PaddyPower (241x)

Guided recognition

Ad recognition

Recognition in general

We asked our participants Which of the following sports betting brands, if any, have you seen advertised (on TV, online, social media, print, radio, etc.) in the last 4 weeks?. Participants could select as many competitors as they wanted from a list of brands. Although, they saw only those brands they previously said they have ever heard of.

Germany
26% of participants in Germany remember seeing Betway advertisment in the last 4 weeks. The most recognised sports betting brand being advertised among German participants is Tipico (77%).8 Learnings: Tipico being the official sponsor of Bundesliga and Bwin officially sponsoring 3rd German division, we see a high share of ad recognition among both brands.

First choice brand

From all the brands that a user considered likely or very likely, we asked which of these would you say is your first-choice brand when placing a sports bet online.

Germany
Overall in Germany, the brand which got selected most often as first-choice brand is Tipico (68%), followed by Bwin (13%). 3% of all German participants select Betway as their first-choice brand.13 Learnings: The plot shows that with 2.66% Betway is amongst the Top 6 first choice brands of participants. Nevertheless Tipico leads with a substantial margin.

Spain
Overall in Spain, Bet365 is most named when it comes to first-choice brands (35%), followed by Sportium (19%) and Codere (14%). 4% of all Spanish participants name Betway as their favourite sport bet brand.14 Learnings: In Spain we find half of the competitors in the 2.5% to 5.0% range. Therefore the gap between those competitors is rather small which could pose a opportunity to climb to a higher position.

UK
Across all participants in the UK, 32% named Skybet their first-choice betting brand, followed by Bet365 (23%).15 Learnings: In the UK the user share shows a more diverse distribution. Betway is with 2.2% in the center of the 14 competitors.

Appeal of Promotions

We wanted to understand Which types of promotions/offers appeal to you most when deciding which betting brand to use?. The participants could select as many options as they wanted. We can see that in Germany, Enhanced Odds and Early Payouts are most appealing, while Spanish users care more interested in Money back and Get and Bet options. UK users are most interested in Enhanced Odds and Money back.

market Money back Enhanced Odds Bet & Get Bet builder Early Payouts None

Likelihood of Recommendation

We asked our users How likely would you recommend the following brands to friends or family? and measured the answer on a 0 (Not likely at all) to 10 (Very likely) scale. In Germany, the average score for Betway is 5.59, in Spain 6.79 and in the UK 5.9.20 Methodology: Participants only saw those brands they previously said they recognise.

Besides Football (99%), American Football and Basketball are the most popular sports for betting among our Onefootball audience.

Conclusion and next steps

Overall, the Betway User Survey has been a great success. The collaboration between both teams returned valuable results, that will shape future strategies and provide an origin for upcoming surveys. In Germany, Spain and the UK we have collected valuable learnings and insights regarding the Betway brand, to better understand the respective markets but also the competitors that Betway is facing in those markets.

Another interesting learning is that the overall age distribution is significantly older than the age distribution of the participants that heard of Betway. The majority of people who know Betway is under 30 years old.

We have learned that Betway has a rather high brand recognition amongst Onefootball users, with about 50% to 70%. Surprisingly this places Betway amongst the Top 3 recognized brands in Germany. Taking a closer look at the recognition on the Onefootball platform we can observe that Tipico and Bwin have a high recognition although no ads were served in the last 2 years. Nevertheless, Betway claims the 3rd place in recognized ads on the Onefootball platform with almost 8% compared to other betting advertisers like Unibet that have 1%.

The overall market situation in the respective countries gets more apparent when looking at the “first choice brand”. Here we can find that in each market there is a well-situated market leader. Therefore the focus should rather lay on competing with the 2nd and 3rd biggest brands in these countries. Overall, Betway is in the center of the provided competitors with a small margin.

As the next step, we could take the learnings about Appeal of Promotions into account and together define a market specific communication plan which takes market-specific characteristics (such as risk aversion in Germany) into consideration.
